Such a scalar 
potential consists of a regular succession of positive and negative bumps of identical, symmetric shape.
For this choice, only odd  appear, the  are purely imaginary and the Hamiltonian matrix
is real symmetric, cf. Eq. (). In some cases, we have employed more general shapes of the 
potential which then lead to larger, complex matrices. It turns out though that the self-consistent Hartree-Fock
potential belongs to the more restricted class of Eq. ().

A characteristic difficulty of the relativistic approach is the fact that one has to determine the Dirac
sea self-consistently, not just the valence levels. In observables like the energy
density or the baryon density
infinities are then unavoidable. They require regularization and renormalization
and hence a certain amount of analytical work. Fortunately, due to asymptotic freedom of the GN model, fermion 
states with large momenta are only weakly affected by the mean field. Thus all UV-divergencies 
can be handled perturbatively. Perturbation theory has turned out to be very useful
to the present study  for other reasons as well. It provides more analytical insight into various aspects
of the phase diagram,
in particular the vicinity of the chirally restored phase where  is small.
Therefore, we briefly outline how to apply perturbation theory to the Hamiltonian
