Baryonic matter at zero temperature 


We first present our results for the ground state of the GN model at finite baryon density 
(). We have to compute the Hartree-Fock energy density for a 
scalar potential ,
 
For standard baryonic matter, the sum over
occupied states includes all negative energy states (the Dirac sea) and as many positive energy
states as required by the prescribed baryon density. Alternatively, one can consider "antimatter"
where an appropriate number of negative energy states is unoccupied.
We adopt here the latter, more economical
way of evaluating the energy density.
The 2nd term in Eq. () corrects for double counting of the interaction energy in the sum 
over single particle energies. Since the self-consistent potential must be
of the form of a local, scalar potential in the GN model, it is sufficient to  
minimize the energy () with respect to  in order to find the full Hartree-Fock solution. 

Eq. () is not yet in a form suitable for numerical calculations.
The sum is badly UV divergent and the bare coupling constant appears in the 2nd term.
